In [13]:
def plot_graphs_by_estimator(estimator):
    '''
    Function to plot all relevant plots for a given estimator
    Usage: plot_graphs_by_estimator(estimator)
    Params: 
        1) Estimator : This is the estimator created using one of the model training methods in PyCaret
                        such as create_model,tune_model etc.
    Output: 
        Series of graphs and charts.
    '''
    plot_types = ['auc','class_report','confusion_matrix','error','boundary','threshold','feature']

    for plots in plot_types:
        try:
            plot_model(estimator,plot=plots,scale=1.25,verbose=False)
        except:
            print(f"Cannot plot the {plots} graph !!!")

    #Plotting Shapely graph
    try:
        interpret_model(estimator)
    except:
        print("Cannot plot the SHAP graph !!!")
    return
# Function test only 
# plot_graphs_by_estimator(tuned_model_list)
In [14]:
def plot_graphs_by_chart(plot_type, estimator_dict):
    '''
    Function to plot a particular plot for a list of estimators.
    Usage: plot_graphs_by_chart(plot_type, estimator_dict)
    Params: 
        1) estimator_dict : This is a dictionary of estimators created using one of the model training methods in PyCaret
                            such as create_model,tune_model etc.Example:{'lr':<object_Logistic Regression>}
        2) plot_type : One of the plot types supported by PyCaret.
    Output: 
        Series of graphs and charts.
    '''
    for est_key,estimator in zip(estimator_dict.keys(),estimator_dict.values()):
        try:
            display(Markdown(f"#### {get_config('_available_plots')[plot_type]} - {models().loc[est_key]['Name']}"))
            plot_model(estimator,plot=plot_type,scale=1,verbose=False)
        except:
            print(f"Chart '{get_config('_available_plots')[plot_type]}' for '{models().loc[est_key]['Name']}' is unavailable !!!")
    return
# Function test only 
# plot_graphs_by_chart('auc',tuned_model_list)
In [15]:
def create_metrics_unseen(column,class_column,title):
    '''
    Function to create metrics/scores for unseen data as a Dataframe as part of predict fucntion for the final_model.
    Usage :create_metrics_unseen(column,class_column,title)
    Params:
        1) column: DataFrame from the predict_model fcuntion for the final_model.
        2) class_column: Target Variable that  needs to be measured or scored.
        3) title: A meaningful name for the final tabulation, usually the name of the estimator 
    '''
    recall_score = check_metric(column[class_column], column['Label'], 'Recall')
    accu_score = check_metric(column[class_column], column['Label'], 'Accuracy')
    precs_score = check_metric(column[class_column], column['Label'], 'Precision')
    f1_score = check_metric(column[class_column], column['Label'], 'F1')
    mcc_score = check_metric(column[class_column], column['Label'], 'MCC')
    metric_dict = {'Model':title,
                   'Accuracy':accu_score,
                    'Recall':recall_score,
                    'Precision':precs_score,
                    'F1':f1_score,
                   'MCC':mcc_score}
    return metric_dict

(3.2) Compare Models¶

Select a Evalauation Measure¶

**Matthews Correlation Coefficient (MCC)**

The Matthews correlation coefficient (MCC), instead, is a more reliable statistical rate which produces a high score only if the prediction obtained good results in all of the four confusion matrix categories (true positives, false negatives, true negatives, and false positives), proportionally both to the size of positive elements and the size of negative elements in the dataset.

MCC = TP TN – FP FN / √ (TP +FP) (TP + FN) (TN + FP) * (TN + FN)

Similar to Correlation Coefficient, the range of values of MCC lie between -1 to +1. A model with a score of +1 is a perfect model and -1 is a poor model. This property is one of the key usefulness of MCC as it leads to easy interpretability.

Reference: \ https://bmcgenomics.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12864-019-6413-7

Choose classification models based on the problem statement of an assortment of models available¶

# This is the main program that automates model creation,tuning and finalisation. Also,gemerates the necessary scores for tuned
# and final model.

# Initialise dictionaries to hold estimators at each step of creation, tuning and finalisation.
predict_tuned_df = pd.DataFrame()
predict_final_df = pd.DataFrame()
final_score_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model','Recall','Accuracy','Precision','F1','MCC'])
all_model_df = models()

# Style fior the final dataframes with scores.
styles = [dict(selector="caption", 
               props=[("text-align", "center"),
                      ("font-size", "150%"),
                      ("color", 'black')])]  


# Creating all models
print("\n Creating Models ....")
model_list = {algo:(create_model(algo,verbose=False,cross_validation=True),\
               clear_output(wait=True))[0] \
              for algo in tqdm(select_algos)}
clear_output(wait=True)

# Tuning all models
print("\n Tuning Models ....")
tuned_model_list = {algo:(tune_model(models,optimize='MCC',early_stopping=True,choose_better=True,verbose=False),\
                     clear_output(wait=True))[0] \
                    for algo,models in zip(tqdm(select_algos),model_list.values())}
clear_output(wait=True)

### Add prediction scoring for X_train here and print it
print("\n Testing Tuned Models ....")
for algo in select_algos:
    try:
        predict_model(tuned_model_list[algo],verbose=False)
        predict_tuned_df = predict_tuned_df.append(get_config("display_container")[-1],ignore_index=True)
    except:
        predict_model(model_list[algo],verbose=False)
        predict_tuned_df = predict_tuned_df.append(get_config("display_container")[-1],ignore_index=True)

print("\n Finalising Models ....")
final_model_list = {algo:(finalize_model(models),\
                     clear_output(wait=True))[0] \
                    for algo,models in zip(tqdm(select_algos),tuned_model_list.values())}
print(final_model_list)

## Add prediction scoring for X_unseen data here and print it
print("\n Testing Final Models with Unseen data ....")
for algo in select_algos:
    try:
        temp_unseen = predict_model(final_model_list[algo],data=data_unseen,verbose=False)
        tmp_data= create_metrics_unseen(temp_unseen,'status',models().loc[algo]['Name']) 
        final_score_df = final_score_df.append(tmp_data,ignore_index=True)
    except:
        pass     
clear_output(wait=True)

Observations:¶

  1. MCC Score: Extra Trees Classifier has the highest MCC score of 0.956followed by KNN of 0.9328.
  2. AUC : Extra Trees, Random Forest,Gradient Boosting, K-Means Classifiers has the highest AUC of 0.99 .
  3. Confusion Matrix: Extra Trees has ‘0’ false negative and low false positives. This is closely followed by KNN.
  4. PR Curve: Random Forest and KNN have the highest Avg Precision score of 0.99.
  5. Prediction Error: Extra Trees has no errors predicting ‘0’ and least error for predicting ‘1’ among all. This is again closely followed by KNN.
  6. We will select Extra Tree Classifier as a model of choice and compare it's performance with other ensemble methods.

Summary and Conslusion¶

Summary¶

  1. Pycaret version 2.2 has been used for ML modelling and modelling phases has been automated to train,test,validate and score all models
  2. MCC has been used as a performance measure due to it;s stability against imbalanced data. Also, MCC igenerates a high score only if the binary predictor was able to correctly predict the majority of positive data instances and the majority of negative data instances.
  3. 11 discrete models have been trained and tested.
  4. Ensemble techniques such as Bagging and Boosting has been evaluated for all 11 models.
  5. The top 3 perdforming discrete models have been picked from the final models and the same is used in blending and stacking.
  6. Finally performance score is compared across all 5 cases and a model with the highest MCC score adn AUC as a tie breaker has been used in slecting the model. #### Model Comparison based on MCC as a performance measure
  7. Discrete Model : Extra Trees with 0.956
  8. Ensemble Bagging: Gradient Boosting with 0.9248
  9. Ensemble Boosting: Gradient Boosting with 0.9244
  10. Ensemble Blending: 0.9157
  11. Ensemble Stacking: 0.9526 with Ada Boost as a Meta Classifier
  12. Comparing models with highest MCC as a performance score, i.,e Extra Trees and Stacking, AUC is higher for Stacking.
  13. Ensemble Stacking is the model of choice.
